               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200918-265-person2478">
                  JOHN 
                  JONES
               <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2478" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2478" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2478" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18200918-265-viclabel1519" type="occupation">milkman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200918-265-victim2477 t18200918-265-viclabel1519"></join>, and live in Tower-street, Westminster-road. On the 31st of August, about half-past eleven o'clock in the morning, I was in <placeName id="t18200918-265-crimeloc1520">Parliament-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18200918-265-crimeloc1520" type="placeName" value="Parliament-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18200918-265-crimeloc1520" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200918-265-off1517 t18200918-265-crimeloc1520"></join>, her Majesty was coming past; I was pressed and pinioned. I put my hands down, missed my watch, and found the prisoner in custody. My watch was produced.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200918-265-person2479">
                  WILLIAM 
                  JONES
               <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2479" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2479" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2479" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw the prisoner in company with two others, whom I knew before. I watched them from the corner of Parliament-street, they attempted to take every gentleman's watch who came near them. I saw the other two get on each side of Jones, the prisoner stood in front, and drew his watch out; I seized him and took it from him as he was putting it into his pocket. About forty thieves surrounded us, and if it had not been for the Bow-street officers we could not have kept him. I found a handkerchief on him, which he said was marked, but it was not.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200918-265-person2480">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MASON
               <interp inst="t18200918-265-person2480" type="surname" value="MASON"></interp>
